# FastAPI Conventions

## Async SQLAlchemy

Always use `async` sessions. Never use sync `Session` in route handlers.

```python
# ✅ GOOD
async def get_recipe(recipe_id: int, db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db)):
    result = await db.execute(select(UserRecipe).where(UserRecipe.id == recipe_id))
    return result.scalar_one_or_none()

# ❌ BAD — sync session in async context
def get_recipe(recipe_id: int, db: Session = Depends(get_db)):
    return db.query(UserRecipe).get(recipe_id)
```

## Layer Separation

- `models/` — SQLAlchemy ORM models only; no business logic
- `schemas/` — Pydantic request/response models; one `Request` and one `Response` schema per resource
- `services/` — business logic (e.g., `extractor.py`); imported by routes, never import routes
- `api/` — thin route handlers; delegate to services, return schemas

## Pydantic Schemas

```python
# schemas/recipes.py
class UserRecipeUpdate(BaseModel):
    title: str | None = None
    ingredients: list[dict] | None = None
    instructions: list[str] | None = None
    notes: str | None = None

class UserRecipeResponse(BaseModel):
    id: int
    title: str
    model_config = ConfigDict(from_attributes=True)
```

## Error Responses

Use `HTTPException` with descriptive `detail` strings:

```python
raise HTTPException(status_code=404, detail="Recipe not found")
raise HTTPException(status_code=409, detail="You have already saved this recipe")
```

## Route File Structure

```python
router = APIRouter(prefix="/recipes", tags=["recipes"])

@router.post("/extract", response_model=ExtractResponse)
async def extract_recipe(body: ExtractRequest, db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db), ...):
    ...
```

## Auth Dependency

Protected routes receive the current user via a dependency:

```python
async def get_current_user(token: str = Depends(oauth2_scheme), db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db)) -> User:
    ...
```
